<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910618-0008</DOCNO><DOCID>910618-0008.</DOCID><HL>   International:   Gorbachev and 7 Republics   Agree on Draft of Treaty</HL><DATE>06/18/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A15</SO><CO>   TAXES</CO><NS>TAXES, ISSUES, LEGISLATION, ASSISTANCE, EVASION (TAX)</NS><RE>EASTERN EUROPE (EEU)EUROPE (EU)FAR EAST (FE)SOVIET UNION (UR)</RE><LP>   MOSCOW (AP) -- President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and theleaders of seven republics agreed yesterday on a draft of anew union treaty and sent it to the national and republicanparliaments for consideration, news agencies reported.   The treaty is the unifying document of the Soviet Unionand would replace one from 1922. Nine of the 15 republics areexpected to sign; the rest are seeking independence.</LP><TEXT>   Seven of the nine republics reportedly signed the draft:Russia, Byelorussia, the Ukraine, Kazakhstan, Azerbaijan,Turkmenia and Kirghizia. Tadzhikistan and Uzbekistan alsowere expected to sign it. Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania,Armenia, Georgia and Moldavia say they want independence.   The treaty would shift substantial powers from the centralgovernment to the republics. It would rename the country theUnion of Soviet Sovereign Republics, dropping the word&quot;Socialist.&quot;   President Gorbachev and the republic chiefs said they hopethe parliaments will debate the draft in the next two weeks.The parliaments then will be asked to choose negotiators tosend to Moscow to work out a final text, the independentInterfax agency reported.   Despite the decision to send the treaty for debate, thereare still several sticking points, Tass said withoutelaborating. But several hours earlier, Soviet televisionsaid Russia and the Ukraine were insistent on denying thecentral government the power to levy taxes.</TEXT></DOC>